How can you modify the Verlet Integration example in Go to include a damping coefficient and plot the position vs time graph using a plotting library?

```
//Verlet Integration Example in Go

package main

import (
  "fmt"
  "math"
)

// Define the initial conditions
var x float64 = 0.1
var v float64 = 0.0

// Define the constants
var k float64 = 10.0
var m float64 = 1.0
var dt float64 = 0.1

func main() {
  // Run the simulation for 100 iterations
  for i := 0; i < 100; i++ {
    // Calculate the force at the current position
    f := -k * x

    // Use the Verlet method to calculate the next position and velocity
    a := f / m
    x_next := 2*x - v*dt + 0.5*a*math.Pow(dt, 2)
    v_next := (x_next - x) / dt

    // Update the current position and velocity
    x = x_next
    v = v_next

    // Print the current position and velocity
    fmt.Printf("Position: %.4f\tVelocity: %.4f\n", x, v)
  }
}
```

output:
To modify the Verlet Integration example in Go to include a damping coefficient, we can add another constant `b` which represents the damping coefficient. The force is then modified to include the damping force `-bv`. Here is the modified code:

```go
// Verlet Integration Example with Damping in Go

package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"math"

	"github.com/gonum/plot"
	"github.com/gonum/plot/plotter"
	"github.com/gonum/plot/plotutil"
	"github.com/gonum/plot/vg"
)

// Define the initial conditions
var x float64 = 0.1
var v float64 = 0.0

// Define the constants
var k float64 = 10.0
var m float64 = 1.0
var b float64 = 0.1 // damping coefficient
var dt float64 = 0.1

func main() {
	// Create a new plot
	p, err := plot.New()
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}

	// Create a new slice to hold the data points
	pts := make(plotter.XYs, 100)

	// Run the simulation for 100 iterations
	for i := 0; i < 100; i++ {
		// Calculate the force at the current position
		f := -k*x - b*v // damping force added

		// Use the Verlet method to calculate the next position and velocity
		a := f / m
		x_next := 2*x - v*dt + 0.5*a*math.Pow(dt, 2)
		v_next := (x_next - x) / dt

		// Update the current position and velocity
		x = x_next
		v = v_next

		// Store the position in the data points slice
		pts[i].X = float64(i) * dt
		pts[i].Y = x
	}

	// Add the data points to the plot
	err = plotutil.AddLinePoints(p, "Position", pts)
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}

	// Set the plot title and labels
	p.Title.Text = "Position vs Time"
	p.X.Label.Text = "Time (s)"
	p.Y.Label.Text = "Position (m)"

	// Save the plot to a PNG file
	if err := p.Save(4*vg.Inch, 4*vg.Inch, "position.png"); err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}
}
```

In addition to the damping coefficient, we have also added a plotting library called "gonum/plot" to plot the position vs time graph. We create a new plot, create a new slice to hold the data points, run the simulation, and store the position in the data points slice. We then add the data points to the plot, set the plot title and labels, and save the plot to a PNG file. The resulting plot should show a damped harmonic oscillator with decreasing amplitude over time.

