In the code provided, you have a parent class called "Ancestor" with a method called "ancestor_feature". To create a child class that extends the parent class, implements an abstract method, and overrides a method from the parent class, you can follow this example:

```Python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod

class Ancestor(ABC):
  def __init__(self):
    pass

  def ancestor_feature(self):
    print('Ancestor feature')

  @abstractmethod
  def descendant_feature(self):
    pass

class Descendant(Ancestor):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()

    # Implementing the abstract method
    def descendant_feature(self):
        print("Descendant feature")

    # Overriding the parent class method
    def ancestor_feature(self):
        print('Overridden ancestor feature')

descendant_object = Descendant()
descendant_object.ancestor_feature()    # Output: Overridden ancestor feature
descendant_object.descendant_feature()  # Output: Descendant feature
```

In this example, the method from the parent class, "ancestor_feature", is overridden by the child class, "Descendant". When we call this method using an object of the child class, it will output "Overridden ancestor feature" instead of "Ancestor feature". Additionally, the child class implements the abstract method, "descendant_feature", which outputs "Descendant feature" when called.

